text: Well as an old guy, I guess I have to throw in my two cents and show how grumpy I am.¬† I'm a big fan of The Four Seasons and I've seen this trailer, along with another one that's more detailed and has interviews with Eastwood and others. That clip shows some scenes that this trailer doesn't show.¬† I see three problems so far, but I'm sure there will be others once the movie is released. 1) The Four Seasons never did choreography, folks. I'm sure they threw that in when the stage play started in order to make them appeal to younger people who would associate them with "boy bands". In the few clips that you see of the real Four Seasons when they weren't playing instruments, they were just standing close together maybe snapping their fingers. 2) They're singing "Oh What A Night" and from the looks of it, it's in their early days because they're wearing suits and bow ties. That song came out in 1975 when Frankie Valli had gotten an entire new group of "Seasons". Frankie had a resurgence in the mid-70's with Grease, My Eyes Adored You, and Swearin' to God and had some hits with these new guys.¬†They had long hair by then, they didn't wear matching outfits, and NONE of the original Seasons were in the band. 3) The same goes with "Who Loves You". They show this one early on and it's the same thing. ¬† So there's a question of accuracy here for me, folks. If it was a Beatles movie, you can bet your ass they'd have EVERY FACT STRAIGHT. Maybe this is just a misleading clip but from the looks of it, someone didn't do their homework, OR, they figure no one that's watching is going to give a damn. Well, us true Four Seasons fans do give a damn.¬†

text: Saw this movie this past weekend. I was really looking forward to seeing the film adaptation of the musical.... and that is pretty much what I got. A film based on a musical, not a musical film. Sure there is music in the film but the magic, dancing and flavor of the broadway musical seems sucked out of this film. It was, I hate say it.....boring. At more than 2 hrs long for a very scant plot line and few musical numbers, I found myself nodding in and out of boredom induced coma. I really really wanted to like this film since they got a top notch cast including much of the broadway cast to be in it, but it seems that Clint Eastwood has made yet another boring film that Im sure will get much praise and acclaim,...I for one am bewildered with the question- Why?

text: Having experienced the magic of the time as a teenager when The Four Seasons impacted the music scene, I thought it would be a good movie to share with my 10-year old. Reading the reviews and hearing from others who took their kids, once again we're turned away by what I believe to be unnecessary R-rated content. When will "Hollywood" learn that you can make good movies and adequately represent an historical perspective without the garbage? A lot of people who want to see this movie will turn away, and for THIS movie, it's a shame. ¬†

text: I saw this movie last night, it was pretty good, the actor who played Frankie Valli also played the lead in the musical (written by Bob Guadio & Bob Crew, who wrote a lot of the Four Seasons songs). I didn't know of all the financial problems in the group--it was kept hidden from the public--also didn't know that Valli lost a daughter who OD'd (also lost a stepdaughter), and that the character "Joey," who told Tommy about Frankie & Bob was, in real life, Joe Pesci (one of the best actors ever). The music was good, hard not to sing along during the movie, but no one can really duplicate the Four Seasons or Frankie Valli. I still enjoy their music.
